      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "I can help you with that! One strong philosophical argument is that all government regulation of the internet infringes on the principle of free speech as articulated by John Stuart Mill in \"On Liberty.\" Mill argued that any attempt to limit an individual's expression, except to prevent harm to others, is a violation of personal liberty. Since the internet is a global platform for expression, regulating it could potentially stifle diverse viewpoints and restrict the exchange of ideas, thus undermining the very essence of free speech. Additionally, Michel Foucault's concept of \"governmentality\" might be relevant here, suggesting that regulations are a form of control that could limit the autonomy of individuals in their online interactions.",
